Our Park serves to unify the city's diverse population, offering public spaces that serve the needs of many by providing engaging and diverse opportunities in education and recreation to residents and visitors. Great parks complement the personality of a city, and serve to unify its diverse populations, offering public spaces that serve the needs of many.Â Bonnet Springs Park is a placeÂ within walking distance to our city's urban core where art, recreation, fun, and tranquility intersect by design. This blended urban/natural park providesÂ spaces to escape, engage, and explore with one another and with nature while experiencing and learning about the extraordinary history of Central Florida. The uniqueness of this location enables a needed connection from downtown to the northwest quadrant of Lakeland, while promoting the economic development and expansion of the downtown area. Even more, Lakeland's strategic position between Tampa and Orlando on the I-4 corridor makes Bonnet Springs Park accessible to many guests. Visit us at Florida's Best Free Natural Attraction! Officials with Bonnet Springs Park announced Thursday that the park on the east shore of Lake Bonnet will open for visitors on October 22. â€œIâ€™m very happy with it now,â€ Bonnet Springs Park Chairman of the Board Barney Barnett said in an interview with LkldNow. â€œI certainly wouldâ€™ve liked to have had it done sooner.Â  Itâ€™s coming in the fall. Itâ€™s going to be a great thing to happen to the Lakeland community â€“ well really, to the Central Florida community.â€ The park was the final gift to the city from Barnettâ€™s late wife, philanthropist Carol Jenkins Barnett, daughter of the late Publix Founder George Jenkins. Mr. George, as everyone called him, died in 1996. Jenkins Barnett passed away in December from Alzheimerâ€™s Disease, but not before giving the go-ahead to fund what its developers liken to New York Cityâ€™s Central Park. Barnett explained that local Realtor David Bunch, who is now on the Bonnet Springs Park board, approached him and his wife several years ago about creating a world-class, natural gathering spot close to downtown. It would be situated between the railroad tracks along Kathleen Road to the east and Lake Bonnet on the west sides; Memorial and George Jenkins boulevards would form the north and south borders. David sold us on it and Carol was interested in it,â€ said Barnett, 79. â€œItâ€™s a shame it hadnâ€™t opened before she died.â€ In February 2018, the Barnettsâ€™ sons, Wesley and Nick Barnett, along with Bunch and Tinsley, announced their plans for the site . The Florida Childrenâ€™s Museum , currently located on Kentucky Avenue across from Munn Park, is scheduled to open Nov. 4 as one of several focal points in Bonnet Springs Park. A rendering of  Florida Childrenâ€™s Museumâ€™s new home at Bonnet Springs Park. Barnett said the pandemic and supply chain shortages stalled their construction at times. But the property has changed drastically since the parkâ€™s announcement and construction began in 2018. Tons of garbage had to be removed, two berms were built to block railroad and traffic noise, a great lawn was created, and multiple buildings, sidewalks and boardwalks have gone up. â€œItâ€™s very impressive to me,â€ Barnett said. â€œA big change from when you saw it and when I saw it the first time when it was just a dirty piece of property.â€ Josh Henderson, CEO of Bonnet Springs Park, said in a news release that they are thankful to dozens of the parkâ€™s generous donors. â€œItâ€™s been a long time coming, and our grand opening will show the wait was worth it,â€ Henderson said before referencing the parkâ€™s theme.Â  â€œItâ€™s about time to escape, engage, and explore at Bonnet Springs Park!â€ Tinsley, who is now president of Bonnet Springs Park, gave an impromptu tour of the park Thursday afternoon. He has been responsible for resurrecting the area from a railroad maintenance yard, with 27 miles of metal rail, and a de facto homeless camp to the crown jewel of downtown Lakeland. Click here to view. LAKELAND â€” The Bonnet Springs Park planners have selected Sasaki, a Massachusetts-based landscape architecture firm with an international reach, to design the proposed 180-acre privately funded park. â€œThe team weâ€™ve selected has done major waterfront-type parks â€” urban waterfront parks have been their niche and specialty,â€ said Bill Tinsley, a former Lakeland Parks and Recreation director who is volunteering his time to the park-building effort. â€œThe broad base of their firm had a lot of attraction for us because we have so many natural elements,â€ at the site, which lies between George Jenkins and Memorial boulevards west of Sikes Boulevard, Tinsley said. â€œOne-hundred years ago someone had a vision for Lake Mirror; with this park it is our vision to wrap downtown Lakeland with an amenity that will have that kind of 100-year legacy.â€ Sasaki has designed a number of waterfront parks including the Charleston, S.C., Waterfront Park, Chicago Riverwalk and Moore Square in Raleigh, N.C. The firm also designed the U.S. Capitol Visitors Center, a three-story extension to the Capitol built underground to preserve the East Plaza, which is now open to the public. The firm also has designed major urban greenspace projects in Shanghai and designed the landscape at Euro Disneyland. A team from the firm will be visiting Lakeland next week for what Tinsley is calling a â€œpower weekâ€ where they will meet with city officials, financial backers and the public for an open house. The meeting will be held Wednesday at the Magnolia Building, 205 E. Orange St. There will be two sessions, from 8:30 to 11 a.m. and from 3:30 to 5 p.m. Multiple informational stations will be set up inside the Magnolia Building to give visitors a chance to see what it takes to design an urban park. The Sasaki designers will spend a good amount of time on the property next week as well, Tinsley said. â€œThe land has historically been earmarked and used for industrial purposes, and this is our opportunity to reclaim it, reverse the environmental impact and transform it into one of the great urban landscapes in the country,â€ David Bunch said. The park, much of which was once a freight railyard, was compiled in pieces by Tinsley and Bunch, a commercial real estate broker, who are volunteering their time to the non-profit park project. The park will be privately funded with the Barnett family leading the charge. The project also will be supported by the sale of the former Florida Tile property on Sikes Boulevard, which planners hope will be developed into a mixed-use commercial and residential area. The park planners hope to have the first phase of the park open by 2020. The park is expected to include trails, a waterfront restaurant and an outdoor concert venue. What are the times? Every day from 10 am - 5 pm. Trams are continuous and crowd size determines the wait times. Can dogs go on the tram? (If they sit on laps? Well-behaved? Emotional support dogs?) ONLY Service Animals are allowed on the trams. Is there an accessible tram with a wheelchair ramp? Yes, BSP has an accessible tram. Is there space for walkers or strollers on trams? The ADA tram has space. The other trams require the walker or stroller to be folded or collapsed. Space on those will vary by the number of riders. Will there be a bus stop at BSP? Yes, Citrus Connection has a bus stop in the Hollis Family Welcome Center parking lot. Are pets allowed in the buildings? Only service animals as recognized by the ADA are allowed.Â  Emotional support animals or other pets are not allowed in the buildings. Is there anywhere my pet cannot go in the Park? Pets are not allowed in any of the buildings, playgrounds, Kiwanis Cares for Kids Treehouse, or the Crenshaw Canopy Walkway. Can I ride my bike on the circulator? Yes, low speed bike riding is allowed on the circulator. Are there distance indicators/markers along the circulator? Yes! What type of food and drinks are available in the Park? The Depot Menu: Chicken tenders, hamburgers, cheeseburgers, pulled pork sandwiches, smoked sausage with peppers and onions, wraps, french fries, house chips, hummus and veggies, salad bar, ice cream, water, soda Rooftop Bar: Beer, wine, and a full bar Welcome Center CafÃ©: Starbucks coffee, pastries, water Can I bring outside food and drinks into the Park? Yes, but no alcoholic beverages. Food and drinks should be for personal consumption and not group consumption. When is the next event? Follow BSPâ€™s social media to learn about our upcoming events. Are there bikes available for rent? Not at this time. How can someone rent a location in the Park for a private event? Please email events@bonnetspringspark.com or check out our Venue Rental page ! Does BSP have an admission fee? No, BSP does not have an admission fee to enter the Park! Is the Park open every day? Yes, BSP is open 365 days a year unless there is severe inclement weather or the Park is closed for a private event. Updates on Park closures will be posted on BSP social media platforms. Is the Florida Children's Museum a separate organization? Yes, the FCM is a separate organization from BSP and has an admission fee. Learn more about the FCM by visiting https://explorefcm.org/. What is the Carol Jenkins Barnett United Way Children's Resource Center? The Carol Jenkins Barnett United Way Childrenâ€™s Resource Center is located within the Florida Childrenâ€™s Museum. You can learn more here . How can guests donate to the Park? Guests can donate while visiting the Park by using the DipJar. The DipJar can be found in the Welcome Center. Guests can also go to our website and click the â€œ Donate â€ button on the homepage. Does BSP accept mobile pay? Yes, BSP accepts all forms of mobile payment. Can you round up your purchase price to the nearest dollar to donate to the Park? Yes, guests can round up to the nearest dollar to donate back to BSP while buying items at the Park. Does BSP accept cash? No, BSP is cash free. Guests can use their own personal credit or debit card, mobile pay, or transfer cash onto a reverse ATM card. Does the reverse ATM card have a service fee? No, the reverse ATM card will produce a card with the exact amount of money a guest puts into the machine. Is the reverse ATM card refillable? No, the card is not refillable. Does the reverse ATM card expire? No, the reverse ATM card doesn't expire. Can the reverse ATM card be used outside of the Park? Yes, the reverse ATM card acts as a Visa card and can be used outside of the Park. Are hammocks, tents, or slack lines allowed at the Park? No, these items are not permitted at the Park. Where are the designated smoking areas at the Park? There are designated smoking areas located in BSP's parking lots. Will the Park have wheelchairs for rent? Not at this time but stay tuned for future updates! Are there pet water fountains at the Park? Yes, all of the green water fountains along the Circulator have a pet bowl attachment! What are the Park's current hours of operation? 6am to dusk, attractions open between 8am-11am. Click here for official hours! What are the hours of operation at the cafe, depot, and rooftop bar? Cafe: 8AM - 7PM Depot: 11AM - 7:30PM Rooftop Bar: 12 - 8PM Are skateboards/bicycles/e-bikes allowed in the Park? Personal devices with wheels are only allowed on the Lakeland Regional Health Circulator and must follow posted speed limits. These devices are not allowed on smaller paths, boardwalks, or indoors. This policy does not apply to mobility scooters. Mobility scooters are allowed Park-wide. Are all Park restrooms open during Park hours? Interior Restrooms throughout the Park will only be open when a staff member is present in the building to ensure the safety of our guests. Outdoor restrooms will be accessible during open gate hours for runners/bikers. Please see the park map for restroom locations. Are there AED machines at the Park? Yes, there are six AED machines located around the Park. AED machines can be found at the Welcome Center kitchen office, Depot kitchen office, Greenhouse office, Nature Center office, and the Maintenance Building office. Does BSP have on-site first aid? No, BSP does not have onsite first aid. In the event of a medical emergency call 911 and then alert a staff member you have done so. Can guests fish in the Lagoon? No, fishing is not permitted at the Park. Does BSP have a lost and found? Yes, BSP has a lost and found. Guests can inquire about lost items at the BSP Gift Shop located in the Welcome Center. Are guests allowed to walk on the grass? Yes, guests can walk on the grass at the Park. What can I bring to the Park? Picnic blankets, low backed lawn chairs, umbrellas (except during concerts), and personal coolers (without alcohol). What is your photo policy? Photographers are often at work in the park. Photography and video and audio recording frequently occur without notice to our visitors. Your entry into the park will constitute your consent to the recording, use, release, and publication of any such photographs and video and audio recordings. What if I have a question that's still unanswered? Please refer to our General Park Rules or email info@bonnetspringspark.com . About Our Vision Our History Leadership News & Updates In the Media Visit Plan Your Visit Education at BSP Park Rules FAQs Get Involved Volunteer Career Opportunities Support BSP Carol Jenkins Barnett Endowment Friends of BSP Bricks Venue Rental Weddings & Corporate Events Other Contact Calendar of Events DONATE About Our Vision Our History Leadership News & Updates In the Media Visit Plan Your Visit Education at BSP Summer Field Trips at BSP Park Rules FAQs Get Involved Volunteer Career Opportunities Support BSP Carol Jenkins Barnett Endowment Friends of BSP Bricks Venue Rental Weddings & Corporate Events Other Contact Donate Calendar of Events Ã— About Our Vision Our History Leadership News & Updates In the Media Visit Plan Your Visit Education at BSP Summer Field Trips at BSP Park Rules FAQs Get Involved Volunteer Career Opportunities Support BSP Carol Jenkins Barnett Endowment Friends of BSP Bricks Venue Rental Weddings & Corporate Events Other Contact Donate Calendar of Events Leadership About The Park Leadership Message from the Chairman of the Board Carol and I have been fortunate to spend most of our lives living in Central Florida, giving us the opportunity to see our community's growth firsthand. This is the community we chose to raise our family, and we could not be happier that this is the community in which our children are choosing to raise their families. When we were presented with the vision for Bonnet Springs Park, we recognized the opportunity to create a place that will be truly transformational not just for our Lakeland community, but for our entire region. More than a beautification project, Bonnet Springs Park will tie together facets that will make our city even more vibrant than it is today. It will offer opportunities for children and adults to engage with our city's history, which is rooted in the land on which the park is being built. It will provide an environment in which you can explore nature in a serene and sculptured setting, a setting which will be unlike any other park in our state. And it will create a place to which children, families, students, and visitors can escape the ordinary and experience the extraordinary. David Bunch and Bill Tinsley envisioned this park, working tirelessly to gather our support and the support of countless members throughout the community. We are excited and honored to work alongside a talented team of volunteers to help lead this project from vision into reality. Together, we will create a place for our community to escape, engage, and explore in Central Florida. There is much work to be done, with more to come, and we hope you will follow along on this journey to create Bonnet Springs Parkâ€¦.a legacy for generations to come. Bonnet Springs Park Â«  Landezine International Landscape Award LILA sponsored by Landscape Forms Winners Jury Records Entries About Landezine Bonnet Springs Park sasaki.com 2023 Infrastructure / Florida / Built in 2022 / more by Sasaki Xinyang University South Bay Campus Gateway Landscape by Sasaki Julong Bay Open Space Phase 1 Xuhui Runway Park Chengdu Tianfu City Landscape Chicago Riverwalk Expansion Great cities are characterized by their parks and green spaces. Lakeland, Florida is a rapidly growing city now distinguished by the new, 168-acre Bonnet Springs Park. At a time when more people are rediscovering the importance of parks in the city, Bonnet Springs Park is a green oasis just blocks from downtown. The park site was once important to the railroad industry but became obsolete, abandoned, cut off from the city, and abused. Building the park involved removing 36 tons of garbage, remediating 300,000 cubic yards of contaminated soil, replanting nearly 3,000 trees, protecting 30 acres of wetlands, and building green infrastructure to treat over 300 acres of urban runoff. DCIM100MEDIADJI_0064.JPG Instead of warehouses or a distribution center, which is what the site was zoned for, now there are playgrounds, gardens, a canopy walk, boardwalks, bike paths, pavilions, a tree house, and 85,000 square feet of community, cultural and educational buildings.Â  Bonnet Springs Park was entirely funded through private philanthropy and brownfield redevelopment credits. No other taxpayer funding was used to build this incredible public asset. It is truly a gift to the city of Lakeland and surrounding communities. Bringing Remediation to the Forefront The siteâ€™s status as a brownfield was a primary factor that influenced the design process. Rather than exporting the contaminated soil or capping the entire siteâ€“two options that would have been costly and with negative off-site impactsâ€“the team decided to incorporate a remediation strategy as an integral component of the design. This decision would go on to inform nearly every aspect of the project, including mobility, microclimate, noise mitigation, and architecture. Perhaps most noticeably, the remediation strategy drove the creation of a hilly topography rarely found in Florida, which is now one of the defining features of the park. In collaboration with environmental engineers, the design team assessed which areas of the site required excavation and developed the grading plan. Intricate modeling and an adaptive design approach created a process that optimized the existing site materials. As excavation began, on-site soil testing continued in order to validate the approach, fine-tune the limits of excavation, and revise the grading plan accordingly. Contaminated soil was used to create two large hills that span approximately 10 of the siteâ€™s 168 acres. The final height of the hills, which reach up to 40 feet, could only be determined once all contaminated areas were fully delineated during construction. To make the area safe for park visitors, the hills were capped by 2 feet of clean soil that had been excavated to create stormwater ponds in other parts of the site. Lighting, accessible walkways, benches, open lawns, and native meadows activate the hills to create exciting new experiences and vistas. Leading By Example:Â  Improving Water Quality The two major water systems within the Bonnet Springs Park site faced environmental challenges. Lake Bonnet is the most polluted lake in Lakeland, and Bonnet Springs Valley, which drains into Lake Bonnet, was experiencing an accelerated rate of erosion along its banks. In response to these challenges, a diverse set of green infrastructure strategies were employed to capture, redirect, and mitigate the on- and off-site watersheds. The new hydrological regime diverts drained water into a new pipe and brings it to a lagoon, preventing erosion of the spring corridor. The first flush of contaminated stormwater is diverted from this pipe to provide stormwater treatment on its way to Lake Bonnet. This runoff is routed through a structural treatment device for debris removal and primary treatment before being released within the Parkâ€™s Botanical Garden, first into an armored forebay, then through a winding wet meadow composed of a mix of native and adapted species designed to slow the water, absorb nutrients, and facilitate hydrocarbon biodegradation. This water passes through a swale and into a primary settlement pond, which serves as an accent within the gardens. The water is then conveyed to a new, nearly 7-acre retention lagoon at the foot of the sloping woodland where it can decelerate, settle, and percolate through a 1,300-linear-foot edge of forested wetlands before being released into Lake Bonnet. This design approach improves water quality and helps restore a sensitive ecosystem. It also provides opportunities for park visitors to experience these new landscapes and be inspired to act in ways that promote clean water in our environment. Inspired by the success of this project, the City of Lakeland, in partnership with Bonnet Springs Park, was awarded a Florida General Infrastructure Program Mitigation Grant (CDBG-MIT) from the Florida Department of Economic Opportunity to add flood storage capacity to the Lakeâ€™s drainage basin through additional improvements to stormwater infrastructure and the natural environment. Bonnet Springs Park - Visit Central Florida Skip to content Go to VISIT CENTRAL FLORIDA SPORTS Open main menu Close main menu Deals & Specials Welcome Center Meetings & Conventions Travel Guide Blog Search Search for submit Events See & Do Eat & Drink Stay Cities & Towns Meetings Deals & Specials Facebook Twitter Pinterest Instagram YouTube Bonnet Springs Park Bonnet Springs Park is located in Lakeland along the I-4 corridor making it accessible to many guests! The Park serves to unify the city's diverse population, offering public spaces that serve the needs of many! The whole family is welcome, including pets! Highlights include the Hollis Family Welcome Center, the AgAmerica Heritage Garden, The Florida Childrenâ€™s Museum, the Crenshaw Canopy Walk, The Kiwanis Cares for Kids Treehouse and more! Admission to Bonnet Springs Park is free. Voted the #1 City Park by USA Today in 2025, Bonnet Springs Park is the largest city park in Polk County. Enjoy the enriching surroundings of this blended urban / natural space at Bonnet Springs Park, situated next to Downtown Lakeland, easily accessible from Tampa, Orlando and Winter Haven. The former site of the longest railyard in Florida has been carefully converted into what promises to be a magnificent facility providing unapparelled experiences from nature, the arts, education and wellness. Itâ€™s all lovingly created in a way that pays homage to the heritage and natural setting of Lakeland and Polk County. The Hollis Family Welcome Center Upon entering Bonnet Springs Park, you will be greeted by the Hollis Family Welcome Center. This two-story building is home to the Watson Clinic Gallery, a coffee shop serving Starbucks coffee and snacks, and a gift shop. Located outside is the Rodda Family Playground which encourages childrenâ€™s sense of discovery and imagination. Watson Clinic Gallery Learn how the city of Lakeland and surrounding areas developed over the years, in the Watson Clinic Gallery. This wonderful gallery pays tribute to the history of Central Florida including its important railroad and citrus heritage. CafÃ© and Snacks The cafÃ© at the Hollis Welcome Center serves Starbucks coffee and pastries. Itâ€™s the perfect spot to grab a quick bite or sit down and work for a while. Also be sure to check out the rooftop cafÃ© next to the Florida Childrenâ€™s Museum ! The AgAmerica Heritage Garden Enjoy the serene beauty of the AgAmerica Heritage Garden. The beautifully sculpted linear gardens provide a natural cover, while you can experience one of the many health and wellness equipment pieces offered in the community fitness area. Also located within is the Joe L. and Karen Ruthven Train Playground. The Kiwanis Cares for Kidâ€™s Treehouse The Kiwanis Cares for Kids Treehouse is 500 square feet aerial sanctuary and promises to be the best kept secret in the Park. Mable the Mosaic Owl Have a hoot on Mable the Mosaic Owl! This interactive playground is ready for adventure. With a slide for a tail and rock climbing on the wings, your kids are sure to have a great afternoon! Southern Glazerâ€™s Wine and Spirits Rooftop Bar After a day of exploring the Park, donâ€™t forget to stop by the Southern Glazerâ€™s Wine and Spirits Rooftop Bar! Located above the Depot, this bar offers full service, two TVâ€™s and a great view of the Allen & Company Family Lawn! Harrell Family Botanical Gardens The Harrell Family Botanical Gardens, located outside of the Event Center, are designed to engage your five senses! Featuring sculptures by renowned local artists, as well as fascinating flora, these gardens are perfect for an afternoon stroll! GiveWell Community Foundation Nature Center and Ann & Ward Edwards Boathouse Experience some of the wildlife that calls Florida home at the magnificent GiveWell Community Foundation Nature Center and Ann & Ward Edwards Boathouse! Inside the Nature Center, you will find interactive displays that showcase the native animals and wildlife of Florida! For the perfect view of the Blanton Family Lagoon, head on down to the Ann & Ward Edwards Boathouse. Crenshaw Canopy Walk The Crenshaw Canopy Walk provides a tranquil way to experience the beauty of Bonnet Springs Park! This unique trail is perfect for getting those daily steps in! Event Center Featuring the Citizens Bank & Trust Ballroom, Wesley Beck Patio, and George W. Jenkins Outdoor Kitchen, the event center accommodates up to 400 guests for weddings and reunions. Corporate retreats, conventions and celebrations can enjoy up to 7,000 square ft. of available space, including the ballroom with the latest in lighting and presentation technology. Dog Friendly This park is for everyone, including your best friend. The park is dog friendly, but furry friends must remain on their leash at all times. For full details check out the General Park Rules . Ways to Explore the Park There are many ways to explore this 168-acre park. You can walk, run, bike or wheel your way through. From taking a leisurely stroll, through to getting in a work-out or even just relaxing or taking a picnic among idyllic surroundings, the possibilities are endless. Music and Performing Arts Music, events, performances and more are important to Bonnet Springs Park! Be sure to keep an eye on the Visit Central Florida Events Calendar for upcoming events! Florida Childrenâ€™s Museum Embrace the future at the spectacular Florida Childrenâ€™s Museum . This 47,800 sq. ft., facility will offer amazing indoor and outdoor opportunities for science, discovery and play. Its two floors of galleries include tons of interactive experiences including a Design Park, where kids can design the vehicles of the future, the City Play area, a re-created city district where the kids are in charge, and the beautiful Watermelon Seeds area where kids have free reign to be their colorful selves. The new museum opened on November 4th. A Lakeland native, Heide empowers our great initiative by sharing over 15 years of experience in nonprofit management and hospitality. Heide connects with and strengthens relationships through clear organizational strategy, project management, and community relations, as she has done with keen insight over a career spanning private and independent sectors. Heide is a graduate of the Crummer Business School at Rollins College with Certifications in Business Management, Executive Management, and Proposal Writing. Prior to joining Bonnet Springs Park, Heide served as Executive Director for Florida Symphony Youth Orchestras, where she transformed an organization with a nearly sixty-three-year-old history into an international force for youth music education. She fostered an impact on thousands of families as Manager of Member Relations at Orlando Science Center. Heide kindles passion for nature and the arts while creating opportunities that will endure in guestsâ€™ memories forever. Heideâ€™s combined knowledge of non-profit leadership and guest engagement empowers her in generating substantial revenue growth, fundraising, event planning, marketing, public relations and customer service. In the immediate future, Heide plans to strengthen relationships with the community and encourage Central Floridaâ€™s residents to escape, engage, and explore at Bonnet Springs Park. Bonnet Springs Park is a blended urban/natural 180-acre park centrally located in Lakeland, Florida. Bonnet Springs Park is designed to create spaces to escape, engage, and explore while experiencing and learning about the extraordinary history of Central Florida. Phase 1 of the park is slated for completion in the spring of 2021. Bonnet Springs Park is a 501(c) (3) non-profit organization with a mission to enrich the community through nature, culture, recreation, and education. The Park serves to unify Central Floridaâ€™s diverse population, offering public spaces that serve the needs of many by providing engaging and unique opportunities in education and recreation to residents and visitors. The vision of Bonnet Springs Park is to be a place within walking distance to our cityâ€™s urban core where art, recreation, fun, and tranquility intersect by design. If you are looking for a way to connect with Lakelandâ€™s diverse community and expand your knowledge while having fun, volunteering at BSP is perfect for you! BSP has many volunteer opportunities with shift times to fit any schedule! Sign up below to learn more about becoming a volunteer at BSP. Student Volunteers High school students in the 9th-12th grade can volunteer at BSP for community service hours for college scholarships. Volunteering as a Group If your business or community group would like to volunteer together at BSP, please email volunteer@bonnetspringspark.com . Groups play an essential role in the upkeep of BSP! Tasks vary based on the season. If you are interested in completing a volunteer project for the Girl Scout Gold Award or Boy Scout Eagle Scout certification, reach out to the volunteer manager at volunteer@bonnetspringspark.com REGISTER TO VOLUNTEER "Being retired and volunteering at BSP is a perfect combination. I cannot tell you how many times guests have thanked me for volunteering or for sharing the information I provided them. It makes me feel good to know that my efforts are appreciated and that I am giving back to the community." Michael Schwam "I love volunteering at BSP. I enjoy seeing kidsâ€™ eyes grow wide at the Nature Center beehive, and I am thrilled to explain how a caterpillar can go to sleep for a few weeks, and when they wake up, they can fly! I love hearing about all the far-flung places visitors are from, and I enjoy the staff and other volunteers who share my love of this wonderful gift to our community. Surely there is a place in everyone's life for the shared experiences that volunteering at Bonnet Springs provides... Where the experiences never stop and the smiles are free!" Andy Crossfield "Being a Science teacher, I spend most of my volunteer hours in Zoey's Butterfly House. I recently started a butterfly garden at our school, and volunteering at Bonnet Spring has helped me learn more about the variety of butterflies and the plants they need to thrive. I have also used the knowledge I have learned to share with my students how important it is to learn about our environment so that we can protect it as much as possible. Being a Bonnet Springs volunteer has enriched both my own life and those with whom I interact on a daily basis." Mark Robbins Check out some of our volunteer opportunities Birding Guide Do you enjoy birding? Sign up as a birding guide during Birding on the Boardwalk which takes place the first Saturday of each month. Help guests spot birds and other wildlife that call BSP home. Cultural Connections Activity Helper Cultural Connections activities strive to connect culture to a STEM or a Nature-based topic. If you enjoy celebrating what makes us all unique, then you will love volunteering for this program! Butterfly House Docent If you enjoy being outside surrounded by beautiful butterflies, then being a butterfly docent is the right fit for you! As a butterfly docent, you will educate guests of BSP about the numerous species of butterflies and plants in the Butterfly House. If you want to spend your days surrounded by caterpillars, fluttering wings, and happy guests, you should volunteer as a Butterfly House docent! Events and Hospitality Event and hospitality volunteers will help in numerous ways during BSPâ€™s signature events. By greeting guests, helping with setup or breakdown, and getting to participate in unique volunteer opportunities, donâ€™t miss the chance to volunteer during some of the most exciting days at the Park! Field Trip Guide Help lead meaningful and fun activities for school groups visiting BSP as a field trip guide! Youâ€™ll oversee field trips for children in 4th-12th grade. If you enjoy educating children on a range of interesting topics, you will love being a field trip guide. Greenhouse Docent Greenhouse Docents educate guests about all the interesting scientific elements of a Greenhouse. If you have a passion for plants, then this role is for you. Gift Ship Attendant Help guests check out their favorite BSP merchandise as a gift shop attendant. Answer questions, advertise upcoming events, and show your enthusiasm for the Park while providing excellent customer service to guests. Greeter Being a greeter is a very important role! As a greeter you will most likely be the first face our guests will see when they enter the Park. If you like interacting with people you will enjoy being a greeter! When volunteering as a greeter you will answer guestâ€™s questions and help them navigate around the Park. Greeters are placed all around the Park in front of our most popular venues, so you will never get bored being a greeter at BSP! History Gallery Docent If you like learning about trains and the history of Central Florida, then you will thrive as a History Gallery docent! As a docent in the History Gallery you will point guests to view our railroad memorabilia and train replicas, one of which runs on a track hanging from the ceiling! If you want to help tell the history of BSP, then being a History Gallery Docent is right for you! Horticulture BSP has 168 acres to upkeep which means horticulture volunteers are needed! Horticulture volunteers help with weeding, mulching, pruning, and gardening.If you have a green thumb then you will enjoy being a horticulture volunteer at the Park. Nature Center Docent Do you enjoy telling fun facts about plants and animals? Then you would love being a Nature Center Docent! BSPâ€™s Nature Center is full of interactive exhibits for people of all ages to enjoy. As a Nature Center Docent, you could help guests identify Florida's feathered fauna by teaching them which bird makes which sound. Or, you could educate guests about the flora at the Park by showing them the wall of jumbo sized flowers. You could even teach guests about the importance of pollinators by showing them a live beehive. If you want to tell natureâ€™s story, then you will love being a docent in the Nature Center! Nuts About Nature Activity Helper Volunteer as a Nuts About Nature Activity Helper and help young kids with a nature-based activity. If you enjoy assisting children with fun hands-on activities, then this is the volunteer opportunity for you. Operations and Maintenance Operations and Maintenance volunteers keep the Park looking great! Assist with park cleanup and upkeep of Park facilities. Recurring Programs Helper BSP has volunteers assist in a multitude of ways at our recurring programs like Adventure Days, Exploration Stations, and Sensory Friendly Events. To learn more about BSPâ€™s recurring programs, click here . STEM Saturday If you love teaching people about science, technology, engineering, and math you will love volunteering on STEM Saturdays! Each fourth Saturday of the month STEM Saturday focuses on a new topic. This is a unique volunteer opportunity that varies depending on the topic for the month! *Bonnet Springs Park does not allow court-ordered community service Invite BSP to Your Community Event! BSP has specially trained outreach volunteers that can run an activity station at your next event or program! Outreach volunteers also educate the public about the park and how guests can get involved. This includes topics such as volunteering, student volunteer opportunities, field trips, education programs, events, membership, and more. Outreach Events that BSP may participate in: School Meetings and Events To educate students and teachers about student volunteer opportunities, teacher workshops, fieldtrips, and other educational programming offered at BSP. College Events and Fairs Talk with college students about volunteering, internships, and job opportunities at the Park. Festivals To run an activity or share BSP with the community. Parades To show support for a good cause and spread joy in the community. And More! If you are interested in having outreach volunteers at your next event, school, university, etc. contact BSPâ€™s Volunteer Manager at volunteer@bonnetspringspark.com .
